# Configuration & Security

## Configuration Management
- All runtime settings in `config/config.yaml` (YAML format)
- Template: `config/config.yaml.template` (committed, no secrets)
- Environment-specific overrides via env vars or CLI args
- New config keys must be added to both `config.yaml.template` and documented in `README.md`

## Config Structure
```yaml
api:         # timeout, max_retries, retry_delay, verify_ssl, version
logging:     # level, format, file_path, rotation_size, backup_count, console_colors
report:      # organization, template, pdf
output:      # default_directory, pdf_filename, json_filename
data_collection:  # sections, concurrent_requests, validate_responses, graceful_degradation
security:    # prompt_for_credentials, session_timeout, sanitize_logs
```

## Credential Security (mandatory)
- NEVER hardcode credentials in source code, config files, or comments
- NEVER log tokens, passwords, or session cookies
- Credentials flow: CLI args → env vars → interactive `getpass` prompt
- API tokens stored in memory only; destroyed after session
- Log sanitization must filter: password, token, secret, credential, authorization

## SSL/TLS
- Default: `verify_ssl: true`
- Self-signed certs: configurable via `api.verify_ssl: false` (warn in logs)
- Always use HTTPS for API communication

## Sensitive Data in Reports
- Reports contain cluster configuration, not credentials
- JSON export must not include auth tokens or passwords
- Sanitize any field that could contain credentials before writing output

## Environment Variables
| Variable | Purpose |
|----------|---------|
| `VAST_API_TOKEN` | API token authentication |
| `VAST_USERNAME` | Cluster username |
| `VAST_PASSWORD` | Cluster password |
| `VAST_NODE_USER` / `VAST_NODE_PASSWORD` | SSH node credentials |
| `VAST_SWITCH_USER` / `VAST_SWITCH_PASSWORD` | SSH switch credentials |
